hen gunfire erupted again. A bullet ripped through my 14 year old son's heart. I received a call from my daughter obviously before she knew her brother was laying shot in the street, telling me to come pick them up that there was shooting going on outside the party. I immediately left but before I could get off my street she called a second time yelling CoCo had been shot. I nearly wrecked my car trying to get to my children. Once I arrived there was chaos, kids and police cars everywhere but the scene that will forever haunt me is seeing my son lay lifeless in the middle of the street while blood ran from his body. I immediately prayed not realizing how bad it was even though there was no movement at all from my son. I gave up trying to run to him because the police stopped me every time. I told myself not to yell or cry out loud for fear of my son hearing me and knowing my voice, putting more stress on him while he lay fighting for his life. Finally the ambulance came, put him in the truck and fled to the hospital. I left soon after only to get there and hear after waiting for at least an hour that my son didn't make it. I then cried aloud and so did the hundreds of kids and people who came in support of my CoCo and my family. We were able to view his body before the police came in to begin their investigation. I saw the scars on his forehead and lip where he fell face-first after being shot and was unable to catch himself. I saw the hole in his chest were the bullet entered. My mom cried &quot;Get up CoCo&quot; to him as I kissed my son and rubbed his hair putting his dreads in place. One of the officers even told me that I couldn't kiss him but later she told me after I asked her if I could again that it was okay. I could see the sympathy in her face.  My life was forever changed on October 24, 2009. My surviving children are traumatized. My family will never be the same. The neighborhood is not the same. My son's killer was an 18 year old - a teenager from our neighborhood who would come play ball with my children or just hang around the neighborhood center. CoCo was a true angel who hated to see people hurt, crying, hungry, etc. He befriended an 80 year old white man and nicknamed him &quot;Buddy&quot;. Whenever Buddy knocked on the door hungry, CoCo would feed him, talk, laugh and dance with him. He loved animals and always found a way to bring some animal home from cats to dogs, turtles and ducks, my son had a caring heart. STRICTER GUN LAWS WERE NEEDED LONG BEFORE MY SONS MURDER AND THEY ARE DEFINITELY NEEDED NOW!<\/p>\n<\/div><nav class=\"sharing\">\n    <ul>\n        <li class=\"facebook\">\n            <div class=\"fb-like\" data-href=\"http:\/\/www.barackobama.com\/stories\/gun-violence\/17219\/\" data-ref=\"fb_like_btn\" data-send=\"false\" data-layout=\"button_count\" data-width=\"100\" data-show-faces=\"false\"><\/div>\n        <\/li>\n        <li class=\"twitter\">\n            <a href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/share\" class=\"twitter-share-button\" data-text=\"Read Jeaniqua J.'s story about Gun Violence, then read more from Obama supporters all over.\" data-url=\"http:\/\/www.barackobama.com\/stories\/gun-violence\/17219\/?source=tweet_btn\" data-related=\"BarackObama\">Tweet<\/a>\n        <\/li>\n        <li class=\"email\">\n            <a href=\"mailto:?&amp;subject=You%20should%20read%20this%20story%20about%20Gun+Violence&amp;body=Hey%20--%0A%20%0AI%20just%20read%20Jeaniqua%20J.%20from%20Danville%2C%20VA%E2%80%99s%20story%20about%20Gun%20Violence%20and%20supporting%20President%20Obama.%0A%20%0ACheck%20it%20out%20on%20barackobama.com%20at%202012%20Stories%3A%0A%20%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Fwww.barackobama.com%2Fstories%2Fgun-violence%2F17219%2F%3Fsource%3Dstories_EMS%0A%20%0AIf%20you%20have%20a%20story%20about%20why%20you%20support%20the%20President%2C%20you%20can%20share%20it%2C%20too.%0A%20%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Fwww.barackobama.com%2Fstories%2Fshare-your-story%0A%0AThanks.\" title=\"Share via Email\">Share via Email<\/a>\n